Title:
catdumper — LSASS MiniDump + in-memory RC4/Base64 + HTTPS exfiltration

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
catdumper is a Windows LSASS credential dumping tool that snapshots the LSASS process and generates a MiniDump, then encrypts (RC4) and Base64-encodes the dump entirely in memory. It exfiltrates the encrypted dump and its randomly generated key over HTTPS to a companion Python Flask server (exfil.py), which decodes/decrypts and writes the dump to disk for offline parsing (e.g., Mimikatz). The project focuses on evasion tactics such as compile-time polymorphism for unique binaries, string obfuscation (e.g., “lsass.exe”), and randomized network timing/packet sizing. It also claims to unhook NtReadVirtualMemory to bypass userland EDR hooks and performs benign API call patterns to reduce heuristic suspicion. Useful primarily for red teams/pentesters researching LSASS dumping tradecraft and defenders studying common evasion patterns around credential access and exfiltration.

Technical Focus:
- LSASS process snapshotting and MiniDump generation
- In-memory encryption (RC4) and Base64 encoding
- Userland API unhooking (NtReadVirtualMemory)
- Compile-time polymorphism / signature randomization
- HTTPS exfiltration to a Flask receiver
- String obfuscation and heuristic evasion via benign API noise

Use Cases:
- Dumping LSASS credentials for post-exploitation (offline analysis with Mimikatz)
- Testing EDR/AV detections for in-memory dump handling and exfiltration
- Researching/replicating userland unhooking and anti-hook techniques
- Building detection logic for LSASS access + dump creation + outbound HTTPS staging patterns

Keywords:
LSASS, MiniDump, process snapshot, credential dumping, Mimikatz, NtReadVirtualMemory, API unhooking, userland hooks, EDR evasion, RC4, Base64, in-memory encryption, string obfuscation, polymorphism, compile-time RNG, Windows API, HTTPS exfiltration, Flask, Python receiver, randomized beaconing